A Sketch of a Journey to the West in the Spring & Summer of 1832
By Virtulon Rich
Completed

The pleasure that one takes in running back the course of years to those once familiar scenes which have occupied a broad place in the arena of youthful exertion, seems to carry with it a lesson that should not be forgotten: that we should treasure up to the Present whatever we may wish in aftertimes to recall. And now, from the rapidity with which the ordinary modes of conveyance transport us from place to place, it becomes a matter of necessity to note down the general features of this country with a sketch of men & manners if we would even think to obtain a correct
Completed

knowledge of the same. Besides, no one ought to be so much occupied per se, as to not labour a little for the benefit of others. Scarcely an individual could be found who does not possess some friend who would listen with pleasure to the rehearsal of the incidents of his life. Knowledge is good, and even a little, better than none. So with travelling, a little is better than none; and in giving a hasty "sketch" of my brief Tour, I shall have gained in my end can I but place on paper what will bring to mind things as they actually occured, aiming at a simple delineation rather than a studied effort to make a "sketch."
Completed

At Whiting I took the stage in the shape of an old Waggon, about 4 o'ck P.M. and reached Castleton, a distance of 23 miles, about 7 o'ck. The slow pace and bad vehicle having been rendered quite supportable in consequence of having had the company of an old Friend who in earlier times had been my associate in our "Alma Mater." At Castleton meeting many old acquaintances, hour after hour passed away in agreeable "chat" til the hour of one was rung and we retired. At 3 A.M. I was disturbed by the rough sound of the coachman & again I took the open wagon and, the Driver cracking the impatient steeds, we were whirled away in "double quick" over the frozen ground, still growing harder.
Completed

I had two acquaintances from Vermont. The situation of the school is rather pleasant - in a neat part of the city - retired from the bustle. The Building is made of brick four stories high, 3 sides inclosed by a handsome open fence, making an agreeable promenade within.
Directly back of the city on the east rises a hill considerable eminence. Here having reasoned with a friend I feasted my curiosity, by a view among the rare from its commanding position. The scenery is highly picturesque - presenting a view of the whole city - of Lansingburg on the north - of Albany on the south with the whole line of the Hudson stretching between, whose bosom seemed a thing of life, so brisk was the commerce,

the Capitol at Washington, and brass, that relation in neatness to most of the "Green Mountain State," that a genteel house in Broadway does to a log cabin of Indiana. The State House stands at the head of State Street fronting to the East, on the highest ground in the city, nearly looks down State Street and commands a tolerable view of the city. The inclosure was about done for this world, but they appropriated $10,000 to build a new one. Some distance to the north stands the Renselaur School, built of reddish brown shine three stories high, occupying quite a large space. The only thing that the Albanians distinguish themselves for is their fine horses and carriages - decidedly superior to any other City in the Union for this. They are too, perhaps, the most aristocratic, the most fond of personal display. There are yet a few of the first buildings inhabitable, built in 1600 - of brick brought from Holland - any person who is at all familiar with the Dutch character will perceive at once here, that he is in a dutch city - hogs and dogs - are among the most numerous street walkers - great want of neatness prevails. As we passed Hudson City we had a fine view of the fishermen, who were scattered about in groups of a dozen in a place to the amount of $1.00 - Sunday, seeming no protection?? to the fish. The fish--unclear I think must have had rather a cold bath--mid-deep for hours. At 10. o'ck eve. The unclear having been arranged. On the following morning the first day of May I took the unclear Boat for New Brunswick. It was rather disagreeable, rather wind blowing a shady breeze from the south accompanied with rain, but in all circumstances there is generally something to render our situation tolerable, even when we are surrounded with unpleasant unclear, for 'tis not necessarily the case that our thoughts should be ritained to buffet the storm. The brisk breeze was to me in this instance a source of delight! The broad canvass which, square above square, tourned to an imposing height, and made the noble vessels seem things of life, as they wheeled and unclear to the fisherman's nod, called up no ordinary feelings.

Arnold nothing daunted by the fire sprung upon his adversary - splintering the bamboo over his head, leveling his foe to the pavement – then the blows, from the naked sord of the cane, fell thick up on his victim. He farther attempted to pierce him to the heart but the sord meeting a button glanced - barely missing the flesh - again his arm was raised about to give the fatal stab when some member arrested his arm. Thus was mortal blood spillt within the very precincts of the Capitol. Heard bleeding like a butcheed swine made his way unmolested

Washington City May 15 having now satisfied my curiosity as to what relates to the Metropolis, I put myself in a way to find new objects on which to satisfy my pressing zeal for novelty. At half past three o'clock P.M. May 15th I took the stage for Fredine? City Maryland a distance of 47 miles. The roads were fine and we rattled? on at a rapid rate. The country isu ninteresting and poor -- population very sparse as a matter of course. The soil is thin, principally yellow sand  and gravel. The timber is mostly oak - quite small.
